10. Open Questions
Many important questions remain open.
Examples include:
What technologies are required for fully autonomous industrial systems?
How can planetary ecosystems remain stable during civilizational transition?
What role will Earth ultimately play in a solar-system-scale civilization?
How will human meaning evolve beyond growth-centered social structures?
What new forms of intelligence may emerge from large-scale technological systems?
These questions represent the frontier of existence-oriented civilization research.
Conclusion
Human civilization may still be in the very early stages of its long-term development.
Technological power is increasing rapidly, and the scale at which civilization operates is expanding beyond the limits of a single planet.
At this moment, reconsidering the fundamental orientation of civilization becomes increasingly important.
A growth-centered civilization helped humanity reach its current level of development.
But the next phase may require a different guiding principle.
Existence → Better Existence
Under such a framework, technological expansion, ecological stability, cultural richness, and scientific exploration can coexist within a coherent civilizational trajectory.
Civilization becomes not merely a system for growth, but a process through which existence continues to understand, sustain, and enrich itself.
